explanation:
- UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs: Direct callee of the target. The check must inspect its body to see if it calls memcmp to compare FunctionName (a const char*) or other null-terminated strings. Provide the function prototype/signature so the next analyst can trace how FunctionName and other char* values are used.
- UT_GetStubEntry: Transitive callee of UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs. May return or examine string fields (e.g. stub names) that could be compared with memcmp; include to examine uses of memcmp on returned/contained data.
- UT_ClearStubEntry: Transitive callee. May operate on stub entries that contain string fields; include to check for memcmp misuse on those fields.
- UT_Stub_FindRetvalConfig: Transitive callee. May compare keys or names (possibly strings) when searching configurations; include to determine whether memcmp is used to compare null-terminated strings.
- UtAssert_Message: Transitive callee. Assertion/reporting helpers often format or compare strings; include to ensure any memcmp usage in assert message generation is caught.
- UtAssert_Abort: Transitive callee. As above, include to inspect possible string comparisons during abort handling.
- UtAssert_GetContext: Transitive callee that may return string context or compare contexts; include to see if its outputs are compared with memcmp elsewhere.
- memcmp: The Standard Library function to be checked. Include its prototype/definition so the analyzer can identify calls to memcmp and examine the types of the actual arguments passed (buffers vs. null-terminated strings) and the length parameter usage.
- UT_EntryKey_t: Type used by the target and passed into UT_DefaultStubImplWithArgs. Include its definition so the analyzer can determine whether keys are string types or structures containing char arrays that might be compared with memcmp.

Rationale: to determine MISRA violation you must inspect the direct callee and all transitive callees where memcmp might be invoked on FunctionName or other null-terminated strings. You also need the memcmp prototype and relevant type definitions (UT_EntryKey_t) to decide if the operands are null-terminated strings rather than raw buffers.
